WEBVTT

00:12.445 --> 00:31.058
♪♪

00:31.059 --> 00:32.459
Good evening.

00:32.460 --> 00:36.101
I'm Helen Mirren, and you're
watching "Documentary Now!"

00:36.101 --> 00:37.839
season 52.

00:37.840 --> 00:40.746
When discussing jazz musician Rex Logan,

00:40.747 --> 00:43.804
the question most often asked is,

00:43.805 --> 00:45.840
"What could have been?"

00:45.841 --> 00:47.608
A man of immense talent,

00:47.609 --> 00:51.655
Rex spent his life
trying to outrun his demons.

00:51.656 --> 00:54.901
In 1999, he stopped running long enough

00:54.902 --> 00:58.986
to be the subject
of the now classic documentary,

00:58.987 --> 01:00.199
"Long Gone."

01:00.224 --> 01:02.056
Season 3, Episode 6
Sync and corrections FunnyFunk

01:02.057 --> 01:06.717
♪ Long gone ♪

01:06.718 --> 01:08.963
♪ A ring ar... ♪

01:08.964 --> 01:10.164
Is that the same?

01:10.165 --> 01:11.632
- Chromatical scale.
- No?

01:11.633 --> 01:13.190
Well, it's chromatic the first time,

01:13.191 --> 01:16.583
and then the second time
descending, it's whole steps.

01:16.584 --> 01:20.302
♪ Long gone ♪

01:20.303 --> 01:23.387
[Guitar tuning]

01:23.388 --> 01:24.693
[Beeping]

01:24.694 --> 01:25.804
What is that?

01:25.805 --> 01:28.138
[Man speaks indistinctly]

01:28.139 --> 01:29.217
Can someone turn that off?

01:29.218 --> 01:30.408
[Feedback]

01:30.409 --> 01:31.194
Whoa.

01:31.195 --> 01:32.750
[Folk music playing]

01:32.751 --> 01:34.446
[Rhythmic clapping]

01:34.447 --> 01:44.869
♪♪

01:44.870 --> 01:47.886
Baxter: Everyone has a story
about Rex Logan.

01:47.887 --> 01:52.740
I remember one time I saw him
buy slugs at 3rd and B.

01:52.741 --> 01:55.248
He was parked outside in a big Cadillac,

01:55.249 --> 01:58.536
listening to Chick Corea,
"Now He Sings, Now He Sobs,"

01:58.537 --> 02:00.449
with Miroslav Vitous on bass.

02:00.450 --> 02:03.265
Now, he's playing it over
and over, and he says to me,

02:03.266 --> 02:07.870
"Man, can you believe the notes
these cats are playing?"

02:07.871 --> 02:11.334
Then he threw up, ruined my shoes.

02:11.335 --> 02:13.072
[Laughs]

02:16.097 --> 02:18.300
I would say it's to be happy.

02:20.335 --> 02:22.670
Woman: Are you happy?

02:22.671 --> 02:25.941
That's a mighty big question.

02:25.942 --> 02:29.110
Yes. I would say I'm happy.

02:36.557 --> 02:39.089
I don't know. You tell me.

02:45.293 --> 02:49.162
Man: Describe Rex Logan
in three words.

03:04.646 --> 03:06.052
How did you meet Rex?

03:19.152 --> 03:22.419
[Cheers and applause]

03:22.420 --> 03:25.065
[Jazz music playing]

03:25.066 --> 03:36.085
♪♪

03:36.085 --> 03:38.612
♪ Solar winds ♪

03:38.613 --> 03:40.971
[Cheers and applause]

03:40.972 --> 03:45.451
♪ Solar winds ♪

03:45.452 --> 03:46.944
Both: ♪ Solar winds ♪

03:46.945 --> 03:49.647
♪ From the depths
of the nebulon ♪

03:49.648 --> 03:53.171
♪ Solar winds ♪

03:58.633 --> 04:00.241
Rex, what's the difference

04:00.242 --> 04:02.621
between jazz and regular music?

04:02.622 --> 04:03.740
Well, Googy, I don't know

04:03.741 --> 04:04.815
what you mean by regular music.

04:04.816 --> 04:06.097
I don't think it exists.

04:06.098 --> 04:08.018
Ah, come on, guy.
You know what I mean.

04:08.019 --> 04:11.169
I suppose there's color and tone

04:11.170 --> 04:15.653
and feeling, various shapes.

04:15.654 --> 04:18.803
Uh, can somebody get the nu-u-u-rse?

04:18.803 --> 04:21.651
[Laughter]

04:21.652 --> 04:23.849
Meola: The first time I met Rex Logan,

04:23.850 --> 04:27.761
he was passed out facedown
in a plate of spaghetti.

04:27.762 --> 04:33.635
Uh, it was a February night at some
place down on Elizabeth Street.

04:33.636 --> 04:35.413
I had come in with my girlfriend
to get warm,

04:35.414 --> 04:40.072
and I looked over, and there he was.

04:40.073 --> 04:43.167
You know, I remember asking
the waitress, "Is he dead?"

04:43.168 --> 04:47.008
And she pointed at the little
bubbles in the sauce

04:47.009 --> 04:50.818
around his face, so we knew
he was still breathing.

04:50.819 --> 04:54.021
Then she put one of those
little bendy straws in his mouth

04:54.022 --> 05:00.761
for a snorkel, and I thought,
"Watch yourself, Carla.

05:00.762 --> 05:03.823
I mean, there is something
about this one."

05:06.506 --> 05:08.378
[Speaking foreign language]

05:17.161 --> 05:19.247
[Laughter]

05:24.254 --> 05:25.418
Drugs.

05:25.419 --> 05:31.024
[Harmonica music playing]

05:31.025 --> 05:34.895
I've known Rexy since we were kids.

05:34.896 --> 05:39.867
We called him Little Rex
or White Rex or the Flash

05:39.868 --> 05:42.029
'cause he was quick with the ladies.

05:42.030 --> 05:45.973
When we were 16, maybe 17,

05:45.974 --> 05:50.158
we booked a weekend
doing an early set at the Copa.

05:50.159 --> 05:54.114
I mean, this is the biggest gig
any of us had ever seen,

05:54.115 --> 05:57.584
and Rex says, "You're gonna have
to get a sub for me.

05:57.585 --> 05:59.967
I can't make it."

05:59.968 --> 06:02.622
I said, "All right."

06:02.623 --> 06:04.758
So we're playing that first night,

06:04.759 --> 06:07.699
and the next thing you know,
Rex walks in with my mom.

06:07.700 --> 06:09.756
She's his date.

06:09.757 --> 06:11.879
Now, I didn't like that shit, you know?

06:11.880 --> 06:14.056
Can't be messing with my mom.

06:14.057 --> 06:15.920
But Rex liked to tease, you know,

06:15.921 --> 06:18.672
so I just let it go at first.

06:18.673 --> 06:21.395
But then, you know, he started
making out with her,

06:21.396 --> 06:27.748
making real hard eye contact
with me while he's kissing her.

06:27.749 --> 06:32.653
Well, you know, I'm about to
knock his ass out when he says,

06:32.654 --> 06:38.195
"Come on, Julius.
Can't you take a joke?"

06:38.196 --> 06:40.994
Well, it went on for another 2, 3 years,

06:40.995 --> 06:43.492
and luckily I can laugh about it now.

06:43.493 --> 06:45.242
No, I can't. No, I can't.

06:45.243 --> 06:49.625
That son of a bitch
broke my mama's heart.

06:51.718 --> 07:16.965
♪♪

07:21.031 --> 07:39.286
♪♪

07:39.287 --> 07:41.088
- Sorry.
- [Speaks native language]

07:41.089 --> 08:09.383
♪♪

08:09.384 --> 08:12.019
Hey. How you doing? How are you?

08:12.020 --> 08:18.025
♪♪

08:18.026 --> 08:20.895
Hey, Greg. Hey. What's going on?

08:25.199 --> 08:27.396
Hey, everybody.

08:27.397 --> 08:29.704
How you doing?

08:34.910 --> 08:42.595
♪♪

08:42.596 --> 08:45.453
[Bells tolling]

08:45.454 --> 08:48.281
Downsworth: A day at long last
which many people here

08:48.282 --> 08:49.915
thought they would never see.

08:49.916 --> 08:52.159
Independence for Sárdasovinia,

08:52.160 --> 08:55.152
the one-time Austro-Hungarian backwater

08:55.153 --> 08:57.398
long trapped behind the Iron Curtain,

08:57.399 --> 09:01.101
has never known
self-governance until now,

09:01.102 --> 09:05.138
all thanks in no small part
to one man, Csaba Mozsar,

09:05.139 --> 09:07.074
and the political opposition movement

09:07.075 --> 09:10.368
he leads and which he calls
the Solar Revolution.

09:10.369 --> 09:13.624
One of Sárdasovinia's
most powerful poets,

09:13.625 --> 09:16.442
now officially its most powerful man,

09:16.443 --> 09:20.655
the first elected president
of a democratic Sárdasovinia.

09:20.656 --> 09:23.012
And while he's almost
universally beloved

09:23.013 --> 09:24.242
by his countrymen,

09:24.243 --> 09:27.472
Mozsar cuts an idiosyncratic figure,

09:27.473 --> 09:29.896
known as much for his love of freedom

09:29.897 --> 09:33.450
as for his love of the
boundary-pushing guitar jazz

09:33.451 --> 09:35.022
of Rex Logan.

09:35.023 --> 09:38.165
♪ Solar winds ♪

09:47.461 --> 09:48.519
Sorry. I-I'm all right.

10:28.091 --> 10:30.030
Logan: Can I have someone
find my lighter please?

10:30.031 --> 10:31.340
I'm always losing my lighter.

10:31.341 --> 10:35.096
It's got, um, Minnie Mouse on it.

10:35.912 --> 10:39.752
[Lighter clicks]

10:39.753 --> 10:41.002
All right.

10:41.003 --> 10:43.503
Man: Is freedom
important to you, Rex?

10:43.504 --> 10:45.605
Yeah, freedom is very important to me.

10:45.606 --> 10:50.411
It's, um, you know, personal liberty.

10:51.012 --> 10:57.384
Freedom, you know, it's...
it's sacrament to me.

10:57.385 --> 11:00.250
That's what I like about
the Sárdasovinians is,

11:00.251 --> 11:02.726
they're very freethinkers.

11:02.727 --> 11:05.058
I met a lot of hip cats here.

11:05.059 --> 11:10.028
[Men singing in native language]

11:12.318 --> 11:17.155
[Speaking native language]

11:17.156 --> 11:19.834
[Applause]

11:27.854 --> 11:28.925
All right.

11:34.502 --> 11:39.521
The story with that one is, uh, uh,

11:39.522 --> 11:41.584
I was really sick.

11:41.585 --> 11:43.699
So this girl, Danni,

11:43.700 --> 11:45.409
was supposed to score for me,

11:45.410 --> 11:48.923
and she got some bad scag or something,

11:48.924 --> 11:51.042
and she almost died.

11:51.043 --> 11:52.772
And they thought she was a corpse,

11:52.773 --> 11:56.817
but she didn't really die,
per se, but...

12:01.838 --> 12:04.142
Uh-huh.

12:06.536 --> 12:09.603
Oh, stellar...
So that's pronounced stellar.

12:09.604 --> 12:11.245
- I don't mean to correct you...
- Stellar.

12:11.246 --> 12:12.475
It's just that...
Yeah, otherwise,

12:12.476 --> 12:15.960
it sounds like Steeler,
like the football team.

12:20.490 --> 12:22.778
Are you just reciting my lyrics to me?

12:22.779 --> 12:24.984
Okay. Yes, that would be
correct, yes.

12:24.985 --> 12:25.906
Oh.

12:27.173 --> 12:28.895
I would read your speeches back to you,

12:28.896 --> 12:31.112
but I don't know them.

12:32.924 --> 12:34.772
You look good. I like that.

12:34.773 --> 12:38.797
You know, I'm part Sárdasovinian
on my mother's side.

12:38.798 --> 12:43.965
She's Cherokee and, um, Sárdasovinian.

12:43.966 --> 12:47.650
So that's why it feels
like home to me here.

12:47.651 --> 12:49.779
You know, when I walk around
in the streets,

12:49.780 --> 12:53.333
they feel familiar to me
because, genetically,

12:53.334 --> 12:55.570
all the streets are in my brain.

12:55.970 --> 12:58.337
Man: Why did you go
with Rex to Sárdasovinia?

12:58.338 --> 13:01.841
Uh, I was pregnant with Rexanne.

13:01.842 --> 13:04.202
I had stopped touring when we had Thad,

13:04.203 --> 13:05.430
but being pregnant,

13:05.431 --> 13:09.033
I just wasn't physically allowed
to fly overseas.

13:09.034 --> 13:11.044
That did not stop Rex.

13:11.045 --> 13:15.022
Why do you think Rex decided
to stay in Sárdasovinia?

13:16.049 --> 13:18.001
Rex was a typical artist, you know?

13:18.002 --> 13:22.429
I mean, he would leave, go on
tour, but he always came back.

13:22.430 --> 13:26.300
And then eventually, he just stayed.

13:29.394 --> 13:31.370
One, two, three, four.

13:31.371 --> 14:02.567
♪♪

14:02.568 --> 14:06.226
[Scattered applause]

14:06.227 --> 14:07.464
Good show, you guys.

14:07.465 --> 14:09.476
I thought the tempos
were all pretty good.

14:09.477 --> 14:13.605
Hey, Yatella, you can't
play substitutions

14:13.606 --> 14:15.138
underneath the solo, right?

14:15.139 --> 14:18.251
If I'm doing a solo, the whole
thing goes out the window,

14:18.252 --> 14:19.686
right, 'cause then there's no root note.

14:19.687 --> 14:22.422
So all these people here,
they're looking at me, like,

14:22.423 --> 14:24.691
they look like I'm making a mistake.

14:24.692 --> 14:28.869
You know why you did
substitutions during a solo?

14:28.870 --> 14:30.043
No. You don't know why.

14:30.044 --> 14:31.564
You just felt like doing it.

14:31.565 --> 14:33.299
I mean, he knows the solo
is coming, right?

14:33.300 --> 14:34.840
You know my solo is coming, right?

14:34.841 --> 14:37.040
So you know when to lay out, right?

14:37.041 --> 14:39.406
It's a disgrace, you know.

14:39.407 --> 14:42.109
And by the way, I don't give a shit.

14:44.829 --> 14:46.500
It's your gig.

14:46.501 --> 14:48.214
You know, I could care less.

14:48.215 --> 14:50.587
You want to go?

14:50.588 --> 14:53.653
Hey, uh, let's buy us
one of those lemonades.

14:53.654 --> 14:55.093
I go, "That lemonade,

14:55.094 --> 14:56.712
if you don't want
to put ice cubes in it,

14:56.713 --> 14:58.291
that's not lemonade."

14:58.292 --> 15:00.160
You know, if I could do
things my own way,

15:00.161 --> 15:01.599
I'd just bring my own ice cubes,

15:01.600 --> 15:03.959
but they're hard to travel with.

15:03.960 --> 15:05.364
Mm-hmm.

15:05.365 --> 15:08.705
And why do you play guitar?

15:08.706 --> 15:10.371
- It's...
- Why you choose that?

15:10.372 --> 15:12.530
It chose me.

15:12.531 --> 15:13.856
That's what happened.

15:13.857 --> 15:20.524
♪ I get along
without you very well ♪

15:20.525 --> 15:23.184
♪ Of course I do ♪

15:25.435 --> 15:29.029
♪ Except when soft rains fall ♪

15:29.030 --> 15:32.425
♪ And drip from leaves
and I recall ♪

15:32.426 --> 15:38.310
♪ The thrill of being sheltered
in your arms ♪

15:38.311 --> 15:43.203
♪ Of course I do ♪

15:43.204 --> 15:47.841
♪ But I get along
without you very well ♪

15:47.842 --> 16:01.611
♪♪

16:01.612 --> 16:05.233
♪ Except perhaps in spring ♪

16:05.234 --> 16:09.195
♪ But I should never think
of spring ♪

16:09.196 --> 16:19.038
♪ For that would surely
break my heart in two ♪

16:19.039 --> 16:25.619
♪♪

16:25.620 --> 16:29.249
What do you want me to say?
Do I want him to see his kids?

16:29.250 --> 16:32.685
Yes, of course I do,
but from what I hear,

16:32.686 --> 16:34.345
he can't come back here
even if he wants to.

16:34.346 --> 16:37.584
I mean, legally, it's a lot more
complicated than that, right?

16:37.585 --> 16:40.840
[Jail door clicking]

16:40.841 --> 16:43.101
♪ Solar winds ♪

16:43.102 --> 16:47.167
♪ From the depths
of the nebulon ♪

16:47.168 --> 16:48.433
♪ Solar winds ♪

16:48.434 --> 16:50.905
[Speaking foreign language]

17:17.387 --> 17:19.869
Man: Did Rex Logan know
about the alleged atrocities

17:19.871 --> 17:21.686
being committed by your government?

17:40.348 --> 17:42.531
This is the last song of the night.

17:42.532 --> 17:43.817
Uh, thank you for coming,

17:43.818 --> 17:47.026
and, uh, it's a favorite of mine.

17:47.027 --> 17:50.599
Uh, it's a little slower,
and, uh, you're really not

17:50.600 --> 17:52.057
the right kind of audience for this,

17:52.058 --> 17:57.104
but, uh, well, I got limited
options right now, so...

17:57.935 --> 18:03.395
Uh, anyway, one, two, three, four.

18:03.396 --> 18:17.432
♪♪

18:17.433 --> 18:21.661
♪ Long gone ♪

18:21.662 --> 18:29.203
♪ The ring upon your finger
and the rose ♪

18:32.176 --> 18:35.809
♪ Long gone ♪

18:36.310 --> 18:42.516
♪ The way we used to hold
each other close ♪

18:47.043 --> 18:50.807
♪ I could call or send a cable ♪

18:50.808 --> 18:54.394
♪ But I just don't think
I'm able ♪

18:54.395 --> 19:01.234
♪ All the drinks upon the table
are long gone ♪

19:01.235 --> 19:03.119
Boy: I know that
he can't leave Sárdas

19:03.120 --> 19:06.172
and that he can't talk about why.

19:06.173 --> 19:09.709
I know that Mr. Logan was
an agent of the American CIA

19:09.710 --> 19:13.516
and that, now that his mission
has been terminated,

19:13.517 --> 19:15.515
he must remain in hiding.

19:15.516 --> 19:19.722
If he makes any attempt
to return to the U.S.,

19:19.723 --> 19:21.220
they will hurt his family.

19:21.221 --> 19:23.924
Man: What do you know about
the Mozsar government?

19:24.533 --> 19:27.931
[Sighs] I only know about jazz, man.

19:41.136 --> 19:49.315
♪ Long gone ♪

19:49.316 --> 19:52.552
Thanks. Thank you.

19:52.553 --> 19:53.920
Man: Do you miss him?

19:53.921 --> 19:55.783
[Laughs]

19:55.784 --> 19:59.812
Man, I don't know how to answer that.

19:59.813 --> 20:02.677
I do, and I don't, you know?

20:02.678 --> 20:04.297
People always saying,

20:04.298 --> 20:07.709
"Isn't it sad
what happened to Rex?"

20:07.710 --> 20:11.400
We all thought he'd be dead by now.

20:11.401 --> 20:13.022
How bad can it be?

20:13.023 --> 20:15.585
One more question, Rex...
When you look back on this,

20:15.586 --> 20:17.440
do you think the experience
of making this film

20:17.441 --> 20:19.368
will make you happy?

20:19.369 --> 20:22.394
Yeah.

20:22.395 --> 20:25.173
Of course it'll make me happy.

20:25.174 --> 20:29.824
Walking around Byog, and you filming me

20:29.825 --> 20:33.359
and making me play the guitar

20:33.360 --> 20:37.639
and talk to people
I didn't know, perfect.

20:37.640 --> 20:41.201
Those beautiful ladies you hired...

20:42.874 --> 20:47.974
...and filmed it
with the camera,

20:47.975 --> 20:50.082
genius.

20:50.083 --> 20:51.411
Let me tell you something, Robert,

20:51.412 --> 20:54.448
you're a beautiful filmmaker.

21:11.439 --> 21:39.431
